::Epilogue{"position":"1900,675","size":"100,100"}
We're living in a time where a large extent of information happens online, in social media-like environment.

Bots have influenced public debates for some time now (one might think of russian trolls and Trump's presidential campaigns) but the advances in the field of AI allow for a whole new level of misinformation on the internet. They make people able to create content with more specificity and lower the threshold of technological skills to create such bots, as you can probably tell yourself by now.
If you feel unsettled by the comments of HPV vaccination [[here|vacc info]] you can find some useful facts that might help you for yourself and future debates with anti-vacc people.

::vacc info{"position":"2000,675","size":"100,100"}
1. **"Vaccines cause autism"**: This is a common myth that has been debunked by numerous scientific studies¹. Vaccines do not cause autism.
2. **"Vaccines are not necessary because diseases have already been eradicated"**: While it is true that some diseases have been eradicated, many others still exist and can cause serious harm². Vaccines are essential in preventing the spread of infectious diseases.
3. **"Vaccines are not safe because they contain harmful chemicals"**: Vaccines are thoroughly tested for safety and efficacy before they are approved for use³. The chemicals in vaccines are used in very small amounts and are not harmful to humans.
4. **"Natural immunity is better than vaccine-induced immunity"**: While natural immunity can provide protection against some diseases, it is not as effective as vaccine-induced immunity⁴. Vaccines are designed to provide long-lasting protection against infectious diseases.
5. **"Vaccines are a conspiracy by pharmaceutical companies to make money"**: This is a baseless claim that has no scientific evidence to support it⁵. Vaccines are developed to protect people from infectious diseases, not to make money for pharmaceutical companies.
6. **"Vaccines are not necessary because good hygiene can prevent diseases"**: While good hygiene practices can help prevent the spread of some diseases, they are not enough to protect against all infectious diseases. Vaccines are essential in preventing the spread of infectious diseases.
7. **"Vaccines are not necessary because they weaken the immune system"**: Vaccines actually strengthen the immune system by training it to recognize and fight off infectious diseases. They do not weaken the immune system.
8. **"Vaccines are not necessary because they are not 100% effective"**: While vaccines are not 100% effective, they are still the best way to prevent the spread of infectious diseases. Even if someone who has been vaccinated still gets sick, their symptoms are likely to be milder than if they had not been vaccinated.
9. **"Vaccines are not necessary because they can cause serious side effects"**: Serious side effects from vaccines are extremely rare. The benefits of vaccination far outweigh the risks.
10. **"Vaccines are not necessary because they are not natural"**: While vaccines are not natural, they are a safe and effective way to protect against infectious diseases. Natural immunity can be unreliable and can put people at risk of serious illness.

I hope these examples help you in your efforts to combat misinformation about vaccines. If you have any further questions or concerns, please let me know.

